solution.p:
To compute the eigenvectors, we solve the homogeneous system of equationts (A-\lambda I_2)x=0 for each eigenvalue \lambda.  When \lambda=3+2\sqrt 2, we have

  \begin{split}
  A-(3+\sqrt 2)I_2 = \amp\mat{2-2\sqrt2 2; 2 -2-2\sqrt2} \\
  \xrightarrow{R_1 = R_1\times(2+2\sqrt2)}\;
  \amp\mat{-4 4+4\sqrt2; 2 -2-2\sqrt2} \\
  \xrightarrow{R_2 = R_2+R_1/2}\;
  \amp\mat{-4 4+4\sqrt2; 0 0} \\
  \xrightarrow{R_1 = R_1 \div -4}\;
  \amp\mat{1 -1-\sqrt2; 0 0}.
  \end{split}

The parametric form of the general solution is x=(1+\sqrt 2)y, so the (3+2\sqrt 2)-eigenspace is the line spanned by {1+\sqrt 2\choose 1}.  We compute in the same way that the (3-2\sqrt 2)-eigenspace is the line spanned by {1-\sqrt 2\choose 1}.

statement.p:
The trace of a square matrix A is the number \Tr(A) obtained by summing the diagonal entries of A:

  \def\r{\color{red}}
  \Tr\mat{\r a_{11} a_{12} \cdots, a_{1,n-1} a_{1n} ;
  a_{21} \r a_{22} \cdots, a_{2,n-1} a_{2n} ;
  \vdots, \vdots, \ddots, \vdots, \vdots ;
  a_{n-1,1} a_{n-1,2} \cdots, \r a_{n-1,n-1} a_{n-1,n} ;
  a_{n1} a_{n2} \cdots, a_{n,n-1} \r a_{nn}}
  =
  \r a_{11} + a_{22} + \cdots + a_{nn}\color{black}.

proof.p:
We will prove the rest of the theorem only for 2\times 2 matrices; the reader is encouraged to complete the proof in general using cofactor expansions.  We can write a 2\times 2 matrix as A = \smallmat  abcd; then

  \begin{split}
  f(\lambda) \amp= \det(A-\lambda I_2)
  = \det\mat{a-\lambda, b; c d-\lambda}
  = (a-\lambda)(d-\lambda)-bc \\
  \amp=\lambda^2 - (a+d)\lambda + (ad-bc)
  = \lambda^2 - \Tr(A)\lambda + \det(A).
  \end{split}
